casual_phenomena_line_2: As regards farming in this Settlement with the exception of a few farmers in the Portage la Prairie distant and about 60 miles up the River from here and at St. Andrew's about 10 miles down the River from here there will be no farming done in this Settlement, on account of fear of the
casual_phenomena_line_3: grasshoppers who left their eggs in the ground in incredible numbers here last fall in consequence of which our farmers are afraid to sow. The young grasshoppers are just now commencing to come out about the banks of the River and other places exposed to the warmth of the sun and from their
casual_phenomena_line_4: warmth of the sun and from their numbers one would hardly feel disposed to sow much now. They may  	however take their departure in time to allow the cultivation of Barley and Potatoes but it is hard to tell.

casual_phenomena_line_2: The crops such as wheat oats and barly are looking well so far, as I mentioned before there has been very little sown in the settlement this season on account of the farmers being afraid of the grasshoppers. But on examining the ground where the eggs had been deposited in different parts of the settlement it was found that a little worm something like a maggot has been destroying all the eggs. So effectual has their work been that there has not a young grasshopper made its appearance yet. So upon the whole we hope to have a little crop in the Settlement yet and will be enabled to avoid the calamity that befell us two years ago.
